<<<<<Modes>>>>> There are four ways to use this container: run it plainly, exec a specific command, shell in interactively, or launch it as a background instance.

        RUN — start a built-in mode
        --------------------------------
        Launches a pre-built mode that ships with the container (jupyter,
        dask-scheduler, or dask-worker). You don't point it at a script — you
        just pick the mode and it starts. The mode name goes at the end of
        the command. Running with no mode at all uses the default (jupyter);
        it's best to always pass the mode explicitly.

          apptainer run --nv --bind /my/code:/code container.sif <mode>

          # JupyterLab with GPU dashboard
          apptainer run --nv --bind /my/code:/code --bind /my/data:/data \
            container.sif jupyter

          # Dask scheduler
          apptainer run --nv container.sif dask-scheduler

          # GPU dask-cuda worker, pointed at a scheduler
          apptainer run --nv \
            --env DASK_SCHEDULER_ADDRESS=tcp://<scheduler-host>:8786 \
            --env DASK_PROTOCOL=tcp \
            container.sif dask-worker

        EXEC — run your own commands and scripts
        --------------------------------
        Runs a single command, or one of your own scripts, inside the
        container. This is how you do actual work — bind in your code and
        data, set any env vars you need, and point exec at what to run.

          apptainer exec --nv --bind /my/code:/code --bind /my/data:/data \
            --bind /my/output:/output container.sif python /code/train.py

          # Pick a specific GPU
          apptainer exec --nv --env CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES=0 \
            --bind /my/code:/code container.sif python /code/script.py

          # JupyterLab, reachable via SSH tunnel
          apptainer exec --nv --bind /my/code:/code container.sif \
            jupyter lab --ip=0.0.0.0 --no-browser --port=8888
          # then from your laptop:
          ssh -L 8888:<compute-node>:8888 <you>@<login-node>
          # open http://localhost:8888

        SHELL — drop into an interactive prompt
        --------------------------------
        Starts an interactive shell inside the container. No command runs
        automatically — useful for inspecting the environment, checking
        installed packages, or running things manually.

          apptainer shell --nv --bind /my/code:/code container.sif
          # Type `exit` to leave.

        INSTANCE — run the container as a persistent background service
        --------------------------------
        Starts the container detached, so it keeps running (e.g. a long
        running dask scheduler or JupyterLab server) after you disconnect.

          apptainer instance start --nv --bind /my/code:/code \
            container.sif rapids-job

          apptainer exec instance://rapids-job python /code/script.py

          apptainer instance list
          apptainer instance stop rapids-job

<<<<</Modes>>>>>
========================================================================================
<<<<<Installing Extra Packages>>>>> You can `pip install` something new right inside a running container — it will work for that session. But the container filesystem resets on every fresh run, so anything you installed is gone next time, unless you use an overlay:

        apptainer overlay create --size 1024 overlay.img
        apptainer shell --nv --overlay overlay.img --bind /my/code:/code container.sif
        pip install <package>

        Reuse the same overlay.img next time to see the package again.

        Note: this container's base environment is conda-managed (the RAPIDS
        libraries live there). `conda install` into a running container will
        fail without an overlay — use the pip workflow above for extras
        instead.

<<<<</Installing Extra Packages>>>>>
